<paragraph id="0D3E36D4BE63FFADFF73F8DB7CAC7FF5" blockId="0.[151,1437,1819,1984]" pageId="0" pageNumber="295">
<emphasis id="3FF5EAC6BE63FFADFF73F8DB7E547F3F" bold="true" box="[151,372,1855,1879]" pageId="0" pageNumber="295">Amended diagnosis</emphasis>
(from 
<bibRefCitation id="69104B25BE63FFADFE58F8A47DEE7F30" author="Foissner, I. &amp; Foissner, W." box="[444,718,1856,1880]" pageId="0" pageNumber="295" pagination="422 - 438" refId="ref1161" refString="Foissner, I. &amp; Foissner, W. (1993) Revision of the family Spironemidae Doflein (Protista, Hemimastigophora), with description of two new species, Spironema terricola n. sp. and Stereonema geiseri n. g., n. sp. Journal of Eukaryotic Microbiology, 40 (4), 422 - 438. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1550 - 7408.1993. tb 04936. x" type="journal article" year="1993">Foissner &amp; Foissner 1993</bibRefCitation>
): Small to medium-sized (about 15–50 µm) 
<taxonomicName id="CA814D57BE63FFADFB41F8A47A477F30" box="[1189,1383,1856,1880]" family="Spironematellidae" pageId="0" pageNumber="295" rank="family">Spironematellidae</taxonomicName>
with kineties in indistinct furrows and terminating near or above mid-body. Posterior end with distinct tail. Cortex soft and slightly plicate; cells highly contractile, showing euglenoid movement.
</paragraph>
